===Etymology===
Contraction of ''[[radium]] [[emanation]]'', since the element appears in the radioactive decay of radium.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|rā'dŏn}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈɹeɪdɒn/}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-radon.wav|Audio (Southern England)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-}}

# The [[chemical element]] (''symbol'' Rn, ''formerly'' Ro) with [[atomic number]] 86. It is an [[odorless]], [[colorless]], [[chemically]] [[inert]] but [[radioactive]] [[noble gas]].
# The most stable [[isotope]] of this element, {{nuclide|222|86|Rn}}.

====Usage notes====
The isotopes <sup>222</sup>Rn, <sup>220</sup>Rn, and <sup>219</sup>Rn were discovered independently, and were called radon, [[thoron]], and [[actinon]] respectively. In 1957, it was finally decided that the name ''radon'' should refer to the element in general, regardless of isotope. ''Thoron'' still survives as a name for <sup>220</sup>Rn today; ''actinon'' is mostly obsolete, because <sup>219</sup>Rn is short-lived.<ref>{{cite-journal |last1=Thornton |first1=Brett F. |last2=Burdette |first2=Shawn C. |date=22 August 2013 |title=Recalling radon's recognition |journal=Nature Chemistry |volume=5 |issue=9 |pages=804 |doi=10.1038/nchem.1731 |pmid=23965684 |bibcode=2013NatCh...5..804T |doi-access=free }}</ref>

